954
00:35:56,587 --> 00:35:59,157
-That looks so good.
-It must be hot.

955
00:35:59,223 --> 00:36:02,093
Did the old dude figure out
the old dude's taste?

956
00:36:02,894 --> 00:36:04,262
OH… THAT'S… HOT…

957
00:36:05,763 --> 00:36:07,665
TIPTOEING

958
00:36:07,732 --> 00:36:09,333
-Did he get you?
-It's too hot.

959
00:36:09,400 --> 00:36:11,035
Are you all right?

960
00:36:11,102 --> 00:36:13,037
It's so good!

961
00:36:13,104 --> 00:36:14,372
It's so good!

962
00:36:14,438 --> 00:36:16,007
THE REAL OLD DUDE LOVES IT

963
00:36:16,073 --> 00:36:17,575
It's perfect for my taste!

964
00:36:18,709 --> 00:36:20,178
You say it like an old man.

965
00:36:20,244 --> 00:36:23,281
A sip of soup after the spicy meat
will be fantastic.

966
00:36:23,347 --> 00:36:24,348
AMAZED

967
00:36:24,916 --> 00:36:27,285
I didn't know salted pollack roe
would taste so good in a soup.

968
00:36:27,718 --> 00:36:29,887
EUN-YEONG BEGINS TO PLATE HER FOOD

969
00:36:29,954 --> 00:36:32,557
She's serving the fried rice
on a hot iron plate.

970
00:36:32,623 --> 00:36:34,559
Gosh, that looks so good.

971
00:36:34,625 --> 00:36:36,460
Let me try the fried rice.

972
00:36:37,028 --> 00:36:40,031
Would the old dude consider it
Korean cuisine or Chinese cuisine?

973
00:36:40,097 --> 00:36:41,432
Gosh.

974
00:36:41,499 --> 00:36:42,567
Isn't it a bit bland?

975
00:36:42,633 --> 00:36:44,202
I'm putting the stir-fry over the rice.

976
00:36:44,268 --> 00:36:45,770
SHE CALCULATED HOW IT WOULD TASTE TOGETHER

977
00:36:45,836 --> 00:36:47,338
-Oh, right.
-She's scorching the rice.

978
00:36:47,405 --> 00:36:50,241
She's pouring over the stir-fry
while the heat is still on.

979
00:36:50,308 --> 00:36:51,976
6. TOP THE FRIED RICE WITH STIR-FRY

980
00:36:52,043 --> 00:36:54,545
Gosh, that looks so good.

981
00:36:54,612 --> 00:36:56,180
You have a minute and ten seconds.

982
00:36:56,547 --> 00:36:58,049
HO-YOUNG BEGINS TO PLATE THE FOOD TOO

983
00:36:58,115 --> 00:36:59,650
He's doing it too.

984
00:36:59,717 --> 00:37:01,118
That looks good.

985
00:37:01,185 --> 00:37:02,353
HE USES AN IRON PLATE TOO

986
00:37:02,420 --> 00:37:03,788
SIZZLING

987
00:37:03,854 --> 00:37:05,456
My goodness.

988
00:37:05,523 --> 00:37:06,924
One minute left!

989
00:37:06,991 --> 00:37:08,960
What else are you doing? You have no time!

990
00:37:09,026 --> 00:37:10,027
Kimchi.

991
00:37:10,094 --> 00:37:12,964
Kimchi? He's cooking kimchi
with only a minute left!

992
00:37:13,030 --> 00:37:14,365
That's already stir-fried kimchi!

993
00:37:14,432 --> 00:37:16,601
Ho-young makes a side dish
with a minute left!

994
00:37:16,667 --> 00:37:18,636
-Looks like kimchi for tofu and kimchi.
-He's warming it up.

995
00:37:18,703 --> 00:37:20,304
ADDING MORE FLAVOR WITH BULGOGI SAUCE

996
00:37:20,371 --> 00:37:22,607
-Is this necessary?
-She said she likes kimchi.

997
00:37:22,673 --> 00:37:23,975
It's because she likes kimchi!

998
00:37:24,041 --> 00:37:26,877
He's stir-frying kimchi
because Yu-jin said she liked it.

999
00:37:26,944 --> 00:37:30,147
He's stir-frying kimchi!
You have 45 seconds.

1000
00:37:30,214 --> 00:37:31,949
EUN-YEONG FINISHES PLATING!

1001
00:37:32,617 --> 00:37:34,418
It smells insanely good.

1002
00:37:34,485 --> 00:37:36,187
Today's dishes are fantastic.

1003
00:37:37,521 --> 00:37:38,589
Can you take this?

1004
00:37:38,656 --> 00:37:40,958
You have 40 seconds, 45 seconds.

1005
00:37:41,025 --> 00:37:43,561
Eun-yeong is done.

1006
00:37:43,628 --> 00:37:45,830
Eun-yeong finishes,
and Ho-young has 40 seconds.

1007
00:37:46,364 --> 00:37:47,932
RUSH

1008
00:37:47,999 --> 00:37:50,368
-What do you need?
-I just need to put these on there.

1009
00:37:50,434 --> 00:37:53,571
-Just like a drivers' diner.
-On a tray.

1010
00:37:53,638 --> 00:37:55,706
-That's amazing.
-You have 30 seconds.

1011
00:37:56,274 --> 00:37:57,975
You're going all out.

1012
00:37:58,042 --> 00:37:59,110
BITING HER LIPS

1013
00:37:59,176 --> 00:38:00,945
Hey, you're killing it with the vibe!

1014
00:38:01,012 --> 00:38:04,448
-He's killing it with the vibe!
-It's like a drivers' diner!

1015
00:38:04,515 --> 00:38:05,750
THE BULGOGI MEAL IS ALMOST DONE!

1016
00:38:05,816 --> 00:38:07,218
Ten seconds left!

1017
00:38:07,285 --> 00:38:08,152
-What about rice?
-Ten.

1018
00:38:08,219 --> 00:38:11,022
-Rice.
-Nine. Eight. Seven.

1019
00:38:11,088 --> 00:38:12,957
-Rice.
-Eight. Seven.

1020
00:38:13,024 --> 00:38:14,725
Six. Five.

1021
00:38:14,792 --> 00:38:16,560
-Oh, no!
-Four. Three.

1022
00:38:16,627 --> 00:38:18,863
-Oh, no!
-Four. Three.

1023
00:38:18,929 --> 00:38:20,498
Two. One.

1024
00:38:21,832 --> 00:38:24,335
SLAMS IT DOWN

1025
00:38:24,935 --> 00:38:27,838
WELL, IT'S IN THE BOWL!

1026
00:38:27,905 --> 00:38:29,240
Time's up!

1027
00:38:30,541 --> 00:38:32,176
Ho-young gave it his all.

1028
00:38:32,576 --> 00:38:33,577
AMAZED

1029
00:38:33,644 --> 00:38:34,879
That's amazing.

1030
00:38:34,945 --> 00:38:36,547
My gosh.

1031
00:38:36,614 --> 00:38:39,650
TWO DISHES MADE FOR SOMEONE
WITH AN OLD DUDE'S TASTE

1032
00:38:41,485 --> 00:38:42,653
No way.

1033
00:38:43,220 --> 00:38:44,455
EYES GLUED

1034
00:38:44,522 --> 00:38:46,557
-<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> isn't easy.
-It's not.

1035
00:38:46,624 --> 00:38:50,895
And now, both dishes were finished
to satisfy Yu-jin's taste like an old man.

1036
00:38:50,961 --> 00:38:53,864
YU-JIN IS ABSOLUTELY PLEASED

1037
00:38:53,931 --> 00:38:56,167
They ticked off every request
that you made.

1038
00:38:56,233 --> 00:38:57,968
-These two dancers.
-Yes, right.

1039
00:38:58,035 --> 00:39:01,138
It was moving to see our two dancers

1040
00:39:01,205 --> 00:39:03,941
<i>do their best</i>
<i>to cook for their fellow dancer.</i>

1041
00:39:04,008 --> 00:39:05,910
You seemed shocked, Jin-young.

1042
00:39:05,976 --> 00:39:07,211
I think

1043
00:39:07,278 --> 00:39:09,880
she was possessed by the deity of cooking.

1044
00:39:11,182 --> 00:39:12,750
-I see.
-The way her eyes changed

1045
00:39:12,817 --> 00:39:14,251
<i>right before she cooked.</i>

1046
00:39:14,318 --> 00:39:15,453
POSSESSED BY A DEITY

1047
00:39:15,519 --> 00:39:18,322
Let's find out what they taste like.

1048
00:39:18,389 --> 00:39:21,025
Chef Eun-yeong's dish,
Hold Your Breath, Love Chicken.

1049
00:39:22,059 --> 00:39:25,863
A DISH YOU WANT TO DELETE
WHILE HOLDING YOUR BREATH

1050
00:39:27,131 --> 00:39:30,735
MIYEOK-GUK AND BEEF STIR-FRY
TOPPED WITH SPICY CHICKEN

1051
00:39:32,136 --> 00:39:35,740
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
HOLD YOUR BREATH, LOVE CHICKEN

1052
00:39:35,806 --> 00:39:38,376
-Thank you for the food.
-I wonder what it's like.

1053
00:39:39,110 --> 00:39:42,747
-This is Yu-jin's time to enjoy.
-My goodness.

1054
00:39:42,813 --> 00:39:44,749
Thank you so much.

1055
00:39:44,815 --> 00:39:48,419
That's the boneless chicken
she eats as a part of her diet.

1056
00:39:48,486 --> 00:39:52,356
I eat boneless drumsticks every day
but never had it like this.

1057
00:39:52,423 --> 00:39:54,191
Right? She's taking a bite.

1058
00:39:54,258 --> 00:39:55,860
But first, blow on it.

1059
00:39:55,926 --> 00:39:57,428
Actual old dudes

1060
00:39:57,495 --> 00:39:59,630
wouldn't blow on it,
and then go like this.

1061
00:39:59,930 --> 00:40:01,065
ANOTHER DAY AT A DRIVERS' DINER

1062
00:40:01,132 --> 00:40:02,767
They can just blow on it first,

1063
00:40:02,833 --> 00:40:05,836
but they always eat it hot and go,
"It's hot."

1064
00:40:05,903 --> 00:40:07,104
I'll take a bite now.

1065
00:40:08,506 --> 00:40:09,774
A HUGE BITE

1066
00:40:09,840 --> 00:40:10,841
She eats so beautifully.

1067
00:40:10,908 --> 00:40:12,343
-It looks so good.
-It does.

1068
00:40:12,410 --> 00:40:14,311
I wonder what the combination is like.

1069
00:40:14,378 --> 00:40:16,747
It's a mix of fried rice…

1070
00:40:16,814 --> 00:40:18,449
LIKE A REAL OLD DUDE

1071
00:40:18,682 --> 00:40:20,284
WELL DONE, DUDE

1072
00:40:20,351 --> 00:40:22,019
…stir-fry, and chicken.

1073
00:40:22,086 --> 00:40:24,555
BOTH CHEEKS ARE FULL OF HAPPINESS

1074
00:40:24,622 --> 00:40:27,191
She's feeling something right now.

1075
00:40:27,258 --> 00:40:29,493
-One second.
-What is it?

1076
00:40:30,895 --> 00:40:32,496
HOLD YOUR BREATH, LOVE CHICKEN

1077
00:40:32,563 --> 00:40:34,432
A taste that makes her dance.

1078
00:40:34,498 --> 00:40:36,333
-She did the chicken dance.
-Totally.

1079
00:40:36,400 --> 00:40:37,401
You did the chicken dance.

1080
00:40:37,468 --> 00:40:38,602
A RARE SIGHT FOR AN IDOL

1081
00:40:38,669 --> 00:40:39,670
Is it good?

1082
00:40:39,737 --> 00:40:42,440
First of all, the fried rice
is seasoned perfectly

1083
00:40:42,506 --> 00:40:44,942
to eat with the stir-fry and chicken.

1084
00:40:45,009 --> 00:40:46,710
-Is it perfect?
-Yes, I love it.

1085
00:40:46,777 --> 00:40:49,814
My fridge barely had anything,
so it's kind of crazy

1086
00:40:49,880 --> 00:40:51,916
that it tastes like
seafood and beef stir-fry.

1087
00:40:52,883 --> 00:40:55,119
I loved that first bite

1088
00:40:55,186 --> 00:40:58,189
mixed with the perfect amount
of spiciness in the chicken.

1089
00:40:58,255 --> 00:40:59,256
SMILE

1090
00:40:59,323 --> 00:41:02,126
-Was it spicy enough for you?
-It looks really spicy.

1091
00:41:02,193 --> 00:41:03,461
I love it.

1092
00:41:03,527 --> 00:41:05,696
It's just how I like it,
level four spiciness.

1093
00:41:05,763 --> 00:41:06,997
-Level four.
-Level four.

1094
00:41:07,064 --> 00:41:08,833
That's quite spicy for us.

1095
00:41:08,899 --> 00:41:11,368
It could be spicy for you, Jin-young.

1096
00:41:11,435 --> 00:41:14,705
-But it looks really good.
-Does it?

1097
00:41:15,473 --> 00:41:17,208
DELIGHTED

1098
00:41:17,274 --> 00:41:21,512
They say Gen Zers mix
<i>miyeok-guk</i> with the spicy <i>ramyeon</i>.

1099
00:41:21,579 --> 00:41:23,113
STILL TASTES GOOD

1100
00:41:23,180 --> 00:41:25,583
That <i>miyeok-guk</i> smelled really good.

1101
00:41:26,150 --> 00:41:27,685
What is it?

1102
00:41:27,751 --> 00:41:29,887
-What's on your mind?
-Tell us.

1103
00:41:29,954 --> 00:41:33,190
-It's just so good.
-Is it that good?

1104
00:41:33,257 --> 00:41:37,294
It's like a mix of seafood stir-fry
and <i>miyeok</i> porridge.

1105
00:41:37,995 --> 00:41:40,264
<i>I love its sticky texture.</i>

1106
00:41:40,331 --> 00:41:42,533
Also, spicy food goes well
with <i>miyeok-guk</i>.

1107
00:41:42,600 --> 00:41:45,803
Must've been hard to eat the chicken
when it was a part of your diet.

1108
00:41:46,804 --> 00:41:48,239
-It looks good.
-I want some.

1109
00:41:48,305 --> 00:41:50,774
-Next, Chef Ho-young's dish.
-Let's get ready.

1110
00:41:51,342 --> 00:41:54,445
A BULGOGI MEAL ANY OLD DUDE WOULD CRAVE

1111
00:41:55,446 --> 00:42:01,719
GOCHUJANG PORK NECK BULGOGI
AND POLLACK ROE SOUP

1112
00:42:02,853 --> 00:42:06,056
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S
OLD DUDE-YA, DUDE-YA, DUDE-YA

1113
00:42:06,123 --> 00:42:08,959
He prepared the dish
with his old dude vibes.

1114
00:42:09,026 --> 00:42:11,061
I wanted to have a bite like this

1115
00:42:11,128 --> 00:42:13,464
as soon as I saw the presentation.

1116
00:42:13,531 --> 00:42:16,300
-What is it?
-Mix it with the soup.

1117
00:42:16,367 --> 00:42:17,568
-On the rice?
-Try it as is.

1118
00:42:17,635 --> 00:42:19,303
But she wants to do something.

1119
00:42:19,370 --> 00:42:22,573
-I thought it was the sauce.
-What should I do?

1120
00:42:22,640 --> 00:42:24,408
-It's the egg.
-The egg's fine.

1121
00:42:24,475 --> 00:42:26,343
She wanted the fried egg.

1122
00:42:26,410 --> 00:42:28,712
-I think she wants it with rice.
-I wanted to put this over the rice,

1123
00:42:28,779 --> 00:42:33,117
-pop the yolk, and mix them together.
-She knows what's up.

1124
00:42:33,183 --> 00:42:36,387
-That's the perfect sauce.
-She knows what's up.

1125
00:42:36,453 --> 00:42:37,988
I wanted to do this.

1126
00:42:38,889 --> 00:42:40,658
GULP

1127
00:42:40,724 --> 00:42:45,563
I love pork neck so much,
so I'll place one piece on top.

1128
00:42:45,629 --> 00:42:47,398
Also, a piece of kimchi.

1129
00:42:47,464 --> 00:42:50,000
<i>He fried the kimchi with one minute left.</i>

1130
00:42:50,067 --> 00:42:51,569
-<i>I know.</i>
-<i>I asked why he was doing it,</i>

1131
00:42:51,635 --> 00:42:54,271
and he said
it was because you like kimchi.

1132
00:42:54,338 --> 00:42:56,674
First, she's trying a bite without soup.

1133
00:42:57,441 --> 00:42:59,176
IN ONE BITE

1134
00:43:01,312 --> 00:43:04,248
-She loves pork neck.
-That has to be good.

1135
00:43:04,315 --> 00:43:06,483
He put in a lot of work
into that pork neck.

1136
00:43:06,550 --> 00:43:09,987
I mixed some Buldak sauce
and brushed it on while grilling.

1137
00:43:10,054 --> 00:43:13,624
Chicken and pork neck
have different textures.

1138
00:43:13,691 --> 00:43:15,059
AUTOMATICALLY
GOES FOR SOME SOUP

1139
00:43:15,125 --> 00:43:16,727
-She automatically goes for the soup.
-The soup.

1140
00:43:16,794 --> 00:43:19,263
-Is that some sauce you served?
-Yes.

1141
00:43:19,330 --> 00:43:22,933
Try the soup as is,
and then try it with some sauce.

1142
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:26,704
-However you like.
-It's chili sauce to add some heat.

1143
00:43:26,770 --> 00:43:28,973
MMM

1144
00:43:29,039 --> 00:43:31,709
-It's a perfect meal.
-It must be good.

1145
00:43:32,076 --> 00:43:34,078
A LUMP OF POLLACK ROE

1146
00:43:34,144 --> 00:43:35,145
My gosh.

1147
00:43:35,646 --> 00:43:37,781
YU-JIN IS VERY PLEASED

1148
00:43:39,083 --> 00:43:42,019
This is the kind of flavor
we're all familiar with,

1149
00:43:42,086 --> 00:43:44,722
<i>but it's even chewier</i>
<i>because it was made with pork neck.</i>

1150
00:43:44,788 --> 00:43:47,625
This tastes very familiar,

1151
00:43:47,691 --> 00:43:50,527
but it's my first time having soup
made with salted pollack roe,

1152
00:43:51,095 --> 00:43:52,630
and it's so good.

1153
00:43:53,197 --> 00:43:55,265
With the mix of these two dishes,

1154
00:43:55,332 --> 00:43:57,201
you could easily finish two bowls of rice.

1155
00:43:57,668 --> 00:43:59,670
REALLY?

1156
00:43:59,737 --> 00:44:02,940
-Will this make the soup spicy?
-Yes, it will.

1157
00:44:03,007 --> 00:44:04,308
-Cheongyang peppers.
-It will get spicy.

1158
00:44:04,375 --> 00:44:05,376
TRIES RIGHT AWAY

1159
00:44:05,442 --> 00:44:06,810
She gives it a try.

1160
00:44:07,478 --> 00:44:09,179
I wonder what it's like with it.

1161
00:44:09,747 --> 00:44:11,248
ME TOO!

1162
00:44:11,315 --> 00:44:13,484
She made it a bit spicier.

1163
00:44:13,550 --> 00:44:14,585
WHAT'S IT LIKE NOW?

1164
00:44:16,420 --> 00:44:20,124
It's quite different
with a dash of Cheongyang pepper.

1165
00:44:20,190 --> 00:44:22,993
I'll have to try making
that pollack roe soup. It looks good.

1166
00:44:23,560 --> 00:44:24,561
ANOTHER BITE

1167
00:44:24,628 --> 00:44:26,997
-It's made with pollack roe.
-Yes.

1168
00:44:27,931 --> 00:44:30,367
SAVORING

1169
00:44:30,434 --> 00:44:33,771
She looks so happy.
She must like how it's spicier now.

1170
00:44:33,837 --> 00:44:35,639
I'm getting dizzy.

1171
00:44:35,706 --> 00:44:37,908
Please continue to try it,
because you'll have to choose.

1172
00:44:37,975 --> 00:44:39,510
Can you give some to Jin-young?

1173
00:44:39,576 --> 00:44:41,578
-Me? Really?
-Jin-young gets a bite too.

1174
00:44:42,146 --> 00:44:43,514
He looks so happy.

1175
00:44:43,580 --> 00:44:46,517
Please make it a little less spicy.

1176
00:44:46,784 --> 00:44:48,719
A BITE OF THIS

1177
00:44:48,786 --> 00:44:50,320
A BITE OF THAT

1178
00:44:50,387 --> 00:44:52,156
CONTINUES TO TASTE BOTH DISHES

1179
00:44:52,723 --> 00:44:54,258
It looks so good.

1180
00:44:54,324 --> 00:44:55,659
It really is.

1181
00:44:56,527 --> 00:44:59,663
Does that soup feel like
Japanese food or Korean?

1182
00:44:59,730 --> 00:45:01,532
-Korean food.
-Korean?

1183
00:45:02,299 --> 00:45:05,035
Please try Chef Eun-yeong's dish.

1184
00:45:05,102 --> 00:45:06,637
I can't believe she added <i>miyeok-guk</i>.

1185
00:45:07,571 --> 00:45:09,440
She made the fried rice bland on purpose.

1186
00:45:09,506 --> 00:45:11,575
The stir-fry is thicker now.

1187
00:45:11,642 --> 00:45:13,444
The <i>miyeok</i> is so good.

1188
00:45:13,510 --> 00:45:14,545
-Oh, the seaweed?
-Thank you.

1189
00:45:14,611 --> 00:45:17,648
<i>Also, there's a chew to the mushroom,</i>

1190
00:45:17,715 --> 00:45:19,316
<i>so it adds a fun texture.</i>

1191
00:45:19,883 --> 00:45:21,185
The chicken's spicy.

1192
00:45:21,251 --> 00:45:22,619
TRYING THE CHICKEN THIS TIME

1193
00:45:23,187 --> 00:45:24,188
Because of the <i>miyeok-guk</i>…

1194
00:45:24,254 --> 00:45:25,689
THIS IS SPICY…

1195
00:45:25,756 --> 00:45:27,558
-It must be spicy for him.
-This…

1196
00:45:27,624 --> 00:45:29,760
but it's still good.

1197
00:45:29,827 --> 00:45:34,331
Mixing the spicy chicken <i>ramyeon</i>
with <i>miyeok-guk</i> was viral, right?

1198
00:45:34,398 --> 00:45:36,200
It's like a luxurious version
of that dish.

1199
00:45:36,767 --> 00:45:39,002
-Right. You know what it tastes like.
-Yes.

1200
00:45:39,069 --> 00:45:41,038
She hit it home
with the slightly bland fried rice.

1201
00:45:41,105 --> 00:45:42,706
-It usually is salty, right?
-Yes.

1202
00:45:42,773 --> 00:45:45,175
So at times, I can't go back to the rice

1203
00:45:45,242 --> 00:45:47,578
because it feels too salty
to eat it with other dishes,

1204
00:45:47,644 --> 00:45:49,580
but the balance is nice with this one.

1205
00:45:49,646 --> 00:45:50,981
Next up…

1206
00:45:51,048 --> 00:45:53,050
FIRST, THE GOCHUJANG BULGOGI

1207
00:45:54,118 --> 00:45:55,519
You can't go wrong with this.

1208
00:45:55,586 --> 00:45:56,620
Man.

1209
00:45:56,687 --> 00:45:58,088
It's like spicy <i>jokbal</i>, pig trotters.

1210
00:45:58,155 --> 00:46:00,124
-No, no.
-The texture is insane.

1211
00:46:00,190 --> 00:46:02,392
-It's chewy.
-It's like spicy <i>jokbal</i>.

1212
00:46:02,459 --> 00:46:05,162
Jin-young who isn't good with spicy food.

1213
00:46:05,863 --> 00:46:08,966
If it's this good,
I'll still eat it even if it's spicy.

1214
00:46:09,366 --> 00:46:10,601
THANK YOU

1215
00:46:11,168 --> 00:46:13,637
NEXT, THE POLLACK ROE SOUP

1216
00:46:14,838 --> 00:46:16,707
It's seasoned perfectly.

1217
00:46:18,275 --> 00:46:20,811
It tastes like a drivers' diner
you want to visit for dinner.

1218
00:46:20,878 --> 00:46:23,447
-Is this because of the pollack roe?
-I think so.

1219
00:46:23,514 --> 00:46:24,848
That and tuna fish sauce.

1220
00:46:24,915 --> 00:46:25,949
DRINKING

1221
00:46:26,016 --> 00:46:28,418
Pollack roe adds a lot of umami.

1222
00:46:28,485 --> 00:46:30,220
This soup is a hit.

1223
00:46:30,287 --> 00:46:32,556
It definitely calls for <i>soju</i>.

1224
00:46:33,957 --> 00:46:35,759
The stronger type, the one with a red cap.

1225
00:46:35,826 --> 00:46:38,762
-Can you share the recipe with us?
-It's simple.

1226
00:46:38,829 --> 00:46:41,398
<i>Add minced garlic, salted pollack roe,</i>

1227
00:46:41,465 --> 00:46:43,734
<i>salt, and a bit of tuna fish sauce.</i>

1228
00:46:43,801 --> 00:46:45,769
-That's it? No way.
-Yes.

1229
00:46:45,836 --> 00:46:47,771
I didn't know pollack roe
had this much umami.

1230
00:46:47,838 --> 00:46:50,440
Chef Ho-young has a knack
for creating intense flavors

1231
00:46:50,507 --> 00:46:52,242
with the simplest recipes.

1232
00:46:52,843 --> 00:46:55,179
People often make soup with salted shrimp,

1233
00:46:55,245 --> 00:46:57,080
but he used salted pollack roe instead.

1234
00:46:57,147 --> 00:46:59,850
I'm not someone who drinks,
but I can feel the hangover disappearing.

1235
00:46:59,917 --> 00:47:01,451
I know what you mean.

1236
00:47:01,518 --> 00:47:03,654
Look at Nam-no.

1237
00:47:03,720 --> 00:47:06,089
He's dining at a restaurant.

1238
00:47:06,156 --> 00:47:08,125
-This is fantastic.
-Is it?

1239
00:47:08,192 --> 00:47:09,760
-I keep eating.
-Did you finish the entire bowl?

1240
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:10,961
He should pay for the meal.

1241
00:47:11,028 --> 00:47:12,496
He's not dining.

1242
00:47:12,563 --> 00:47:14,331
He's getting paid right now.

1243
00:47:15,199 --> 00:47:18,268
DON'T WORRY, WE'LL TAKE OUT
WHATEVER YOU HAD FROM YOUR PAY

1244
00:47:18,335 --> 00:47:21,038
It's time for you to make a decision.

1245
00:47:21,104 --> 00:47:22,472
The two had a cook-off titled

1246
00:47:22,539 --> 00:47:24,107
Food for the Old Dude's Taste.

1247
00:47:24,174 --> 00:47:26,076
<i>Press one to pick Eun-yeong.</i>

1248
00:47:26,143 --> 00:47:27,244
<i>Press one for Eun-yeong.</i>

1249
00:47:27,311 --> 00:47:28,879
<i>Press two for Ho-young.</i>

1250
00:47:30,280 --> 00:47:33,417
Which one of them was chosen by Yu-jin?

1251
00:47:33,483 --> 00:47:36,186
Let's find out the result. Show us!

1252
00:47:36,253 --> 00:47:37,621
-Let's see.
-Gosh.

1253
00:47:37,688 --> 00:47:39,923
She's Gen Z but eats like an old dude.

1254
00:47:39,990 --> 00:47:42,626
Who did our good old Yu-jin pick?

1255
00:47:42,693 --> 00:47:44,494
Food for the Old Dude's Taste.

1256
00:47:44,561 --> 00:47:45,996
Did she choose Ho-young

1257
00:47:46,063 --> 00:47:47,297
or Eun-yeong?

1258
00:47:47,364 --> 00:47:49,433
Ho-young or Eun-yeong?

1259
00:47:49,499 --> 00:47:51,235
Who'll take the star?

1260
00:47:51,301 --> 00:47:52,669
Who did Yu-jin choose?

1261
00:47:52,736 --> 00:47:54,137
Who won?

1262
00:47:54,204 --> 00:47:57,007
Whose dish did she like better?

1263
00:47:57,074 --> 00:47:58,609
It was Ho-young!

1264
00:47:58,675 --> 00:48:00,510
OLD DUDE-YA, DUDE-YA, DUDE-YA WINS

1265
00:48:00,577 --> 00:48:03,981
-Jung Ho-young wins!
-"Old Dude-ya, Dude-ya, Dude-ya."

1266
00:48:04,548 --> 00:48:07,718
THE REAL OLD DUDE'S VICTORY

1267
00:48:07,784 --> 00:48:10,320
-The old dude wins. You need soup.
-Why did you choose him?

1268
00:48:10,387 --> 00:48:12,856
-Both dishes…
-It was good.

1269
00:48:12,923 --> 00:48:16,026
…were perfect for my taste
with the perfect amount of spiciness.

1270
00:48:16,093 --> 00:48:18,595
But what I ordered was a dish
to satisfy that old dude's taste.

1271
00:48:18,662 --> 00:48:20,964
-And in that light…
-She's right.

1272
00:48:21,031 --> 00:48:24,201
<i>…the presentation already had</i>
<i>a strong drivers' diner feel to it.</i>

1273
00:48:24,268 --> 00:48:25,402
-That vibe.
-Yes.

1274
00:48:25,469 --> 00:48:27,304
<i>I was already quite full,</i>

1275
00:48:27,371 --> 00:48:28,872
<i>but I found myself continuing to eat</i>

1276
00:48:28,939 --> 00:48:31,275
<i>since there were</i>
<i>so many different combinations to try.</i>

1277
00:48:31,341 --> 00:48:33,143
<i>I didn't just add the sauce to the soup.</i>

1278
00:48:33,210 --> 00:48:35,279
<i>It was delicious over rice too.</i>

1279
00:48:35,345 --> 00:48:36,914
THIS IS DELICIOUS TOO

1280
00:48:36,980 --> 00:48:39,616
This combination was simply perfect.

1281
00:48:39,683 --> 00:48:43,787
-That's why I had to pick this.
-You're right.

1282
00:48:43,854 --> 00:48:46,556
Please put a star above his name tag.

1283
00:48:46,623 --> 00:48:49,226
Ho-young takes his second victory.

1284
00:48:49,293 --> 00:48:50,294
Please put it here.

1285
00:48:50,360 --> 00:48:52,562
Thank you for the meal.

1286
00:48:53,130 --> 00:48:56,767
WE WILL CONTINUE TO CHEER
THE DANCING LIFE FOR THESE TWO!

1287
00:48:56,833 --> 00:49:00,871
<i>We're about to begin the second cook-off</i>
<i>with Yu-jin's ingredients.</i>

1288
00:49:00,938 --> 00:49:04,741
The GVG,
the Good Vibes Guy, Chef Jong-won,

1289
00:49:04,808 --> 00:49:05,909
versus GST,

1290
00:49:05,976 --> 00:49:08,445
a Guy who eats So much Trans-fat.

1291
00:49:09,780 --> 00:49:10,881
Isn't that right?

1292
00:49:10,948 --> 00:49:11,949
It sounds about right.

1293
00:49:12,015 --> 00:49:13,650
A Guy Serious about Trends.

1294
00:49:13,717 --> 00:49:16,286
A Guy Serious about Trends, GST. Sorry.

1295
00:49:16,353 --> 00:49:20,157
A Guy Serious about Trends,
Chef Sung-jun is up against him.

1296
00:49:20,223 --> 00:49:21,358
A Snack for Gen MZ.

1297
00:49:21,425 --> 00:49:22,426
Sung-jun claims that

1298
00:49:22,492 --> 00:49:24,161
he knows what Gen MZ are all about.

1299
00:49:24,227 --> 00:49:27,331
I know all about the hottest viral foods,
especially desserts,

1300
00:49:27,397 --> 00:49:28,398
and I try them all.

1301
00:49:28,465 --> 00:49:31,868
Dubai chewy cookie?
I had it daily for four months.

1302
00:49:31,935 --> 00:49:33,270
His face looks like one now.

1303
00:49:33,337 --> 00:49:35,706
You're right. Before DCC,

1304
00:49:35,772 --> 00:49:37,240
there was the hottest dessert

1305
00:49:37,307 --> 00:49:39,743
-all around Korean in the year 2024.
-What was it?

1306
00:49:39,810 --> 00:49:42,612
-<i>Tanghulu</i>?
-My chestnut tiramisu.

1307
00:49:42,679 --> 00:49:45,248
-<i>Tang, tang, hulu, hulu</i>
-Sung-jun's chestnut tiramisu.

1308
00:49:45,315 --> 00:49:47,484
-You're an expert on Gen MZ snacks.
-I am.

1309
00:49:47,551 --> 00:49:51,021
Chef Jong-won also said
he feels confident about the order.

1310
00:49:51,088 --> 00:49:52,756
-Is he?
-He said he got this.

1311
00:49:52,823 --> 00:49:56,326
"M" in MZ actually stands for Millennials,
starting for those born in 1980.

1312
00:49:56,393 --> 00:49:58,895
So I'm also a part of Gen MZ, Millennials.

1313
00:49:58,962 --> 00:50:01,531
Also, to connect better
with my Gen MZ staff members,

1314
00:50:01,598 --> 00:50:03,200
I held a Dubai chewy cookie tournament.

1315
00:50:03,266 --> 00:50:04,868
-Yes, I saw him do that.
-That's fun.

1316
00:50:04,935 --> 00:50:06,670
I've been making my share of desserts.

1317
00:50:06,737 --> 00:50:09,272
You must communicate with them often.

1318
00:50:09,339 --> 00:50:10,907
What is it, Sung-jun?

1319
00:50:10,974 --> 00:50:13,110
As a representative of Gen Z,

1320
00:50:13,176 --> 00:50:16,580
I just tried putting myself
in the shoes of his staff.

1321
00:50:16,646 --> 00:50:18,448
If I were them, I would think,

1322
00:50:18,515 --> 00:50:21,051
"Why won't he let us rest?
Why does he make us do this?"

1323
00:50:21,118 --> 00:50:22,252
NO, THAT CAN'T BE TRUE

1324
00:50:22,319 --> 00:50:23,820
It must be a hassle.

1325
00:50:23,887 --> 00:50:27,491
Actually, Chef Sung-jun
is a textbook Gen Z kid.

1326
00:50:27,557 --> 00:50:30,193
-He never comes to our team dinners.
-He doesn't.

1327
00:50:30,260 --> 00:50:32,596
Nam-no always comes and grills meat,

1328
00:50:32,662 --> 00:50:34,765
-and offers a piece to everyone.
-He doesn't come.

1329
00:50:34,831 --> 00:50:35,832
Here's a shocking fact.

1330
00:50:35,899 --> 00:50:36,933
A shocking fact.

1331
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:38,935
I was at that team dinner.

1332
00:50:39,002 --> 00:50:40,437
You were there?

1333
00:50:40,504 --> 00:50:43,206
-You were?
-I was sitting right across from you.

1334
00:50:43,273 --> 00:50:44,274
You were there?

1335
00:50:44,341 --> 00:50:46,076
-I even grilled the meat.
-He was there!

1336
00:50:46,143 --> 00:50:48,378
NEXT TO NAM-NO,
WHO'S HOLDING THE STOVEPIPE

1337
00:50:48,445 --> 00:50:51,081
SUNG-JUN WAS SITTING
RIGHT ACROSS FROM POONG

1338
00:50:51,148 --> 00:50:52,816
-He was there.
-He was?

1339
00:50:52,883 --> 00:50:54,551
This is like a ghost story.

1340
00:50:54,618 --> 00:50:56,520
-You didn't talk? Was that why?
-Not at all.

1341
00:50:56,586 --> 00:50:57,954
He had zero presence.

1342
00:50:58,021 --> 00:50:59,156
SUNG-JUN HAS NO PRESENCE

1343
00:51:00,924 --> 00:51:02,125
NEXT TIME, I'LL HAVE EVERYONE REMEMBER ME

1344
00:51:02,192 --> 00:51:04,327
For the five-minute check in this round,

1345
00:51:04,394 --> 00:51:08,065
-our Mr. No-Star Chef will go.
-Yes, right.

1346
00:51:08,131 --> 00:51:11,068
-Mr. No-Star Chef?
-Mr. No-Star Chef.

1347
00:51:11,134 --> 00:51:13,336
-Please do that for us.
-This spoon is too small.

1348
00:51:14,171 --> 00:51:16,139
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
BRAISED CHESTNUT, FIG JAM

1349
00:51:16,206 --> 00:51:18,341
CREAM CHEESE, GREEK YOGURT,
MILK, LEMON JUICE, PANCAKE MIX

1350
00:51:18,408 --> 00:51:20,610
The name of my dish is…

1351
00:51:21,344 --> 00:51:22,345
DCP.

1352
00:51:23,513 --> 00:51:25,048
-DCC?
-DCP.

1353
00:51:25,115 --> 00:51:27,617
-You're making Dubai chewy cookies?
-DCP, not DCC?

1354
00:51:27,684 --> 00:51:30,220
I'm going to mix
my signature dessert with a new idea.

1355
00:51:30,287 --> 00:51:35,459
Dubai Chewy
chestnut tirami-soufflé Pancake.

1356
00:51:35,525 --> 00:51:37,694
What are you talking about?

1357
00:51:37,761 --> 00:51:41,898
Dubai Chewy
chestnut tirami-soufflé Pancake.

1358
00:51:41,965 --> 00:51:45,302
That's the longest name
after Tikki Tikki Tembo.

1359
00:51:45,368 --> 00:51:48,405
-Tikki Tikki Tembo-no Sa Rembo-chari…
-Tikki Tikki Tembo-no Sa Rembo-chari…

1360
00:51:48,472 --> 00:51:50,207
Here's the key point.

1361
00:51:50,273 --> 00:51:51,608
These days,

1362
00:51:51,675 --> 00:51:54,411
the strands you use to make DCC,
kadayif, is always sold out.

1363
00:51:54,478 --> 00:51:55,912
-Yes.
-It's hard to get.

1364
00:51:55,979 --> 00:51:59,282
That's why I'll make it right here.

1365
00:51:59,349 --> 00:52:00,517
-Really?
-Whoa.

1366
00:52:00,584 --> 00:52:01,585
-You'll make it?
-Can you do that?

1367
00:52:01,651 --> 00:52:03,620
I'll make it and use it as an ingredient.

1368
00:52:03,687 --> 00:52:05,455
-Really?
-Also, I'll make meringue

1369
00:52:05,522 --> 00:52:07,124
and make thick soufflé pancakes.

1370
00:52:07,190 --> 00:52:08,992
-By hand?
-And then,

1371
00:52:09,059 --> 00:52:10,494
instead of pistachio cream,

1372
00:52:10,560 --> 00:52:13,497
I'll mix chestnut cream with kadayif

1373
00:52:13,563 --> 00:52:15,532
-and stick it in the middle.
-Really?

1374
00:52:15,599 --> 00:52:17,267
You won't have enough time.

1375
00:52:17,334 --> 00:52:19,469
-I don't think I will.
-It's impossible.

1376
00:52:19,936 --> 00:52:21,438
WHY ARE YOU SO COCKY?

1377
00:52:21,505 --> 00:52:24,908
-Let's say you can make kadayif.
-No, you can do this.

1378
00:52:24,975 --> 00:52:29,346
That's not it, though.
He has to roast it and make it crispy.

1379
00:52:29,412 --> 00:52:32,482
That's the only way it'll stay crispy
when it's mixed with cream.

1380
00:52:32,549 --> 00:52:33,917
Otherwise, it'll turn soggy.

1381
00:52:33,984 --> 00:52:35,919
-You're explaining it like a chef.
-Is that okay?

1382
00:52:36,586 --> 00:52:39,289
Chefs should never say no
to a difficult challenge.

1383
00:52:40,357 --> 00:52:41,525
Where did you pick this up?

1384
00:52:41,591 --> 00:52:43,693
THEY ALSO PICK IT UP

1385
00:52:43,760 --> 00:52:47,230
Also, my favorite member of IVE,
An Yu-jin, is here today, so…

1386
00:52:47,797 --> 00:52:49,232
AN YU-JIN?

1387
00:52:49,299 --> 00:52:50,467
Just "Yu-jin."

1388
00:52:50,534 --> 00:52:52,369
-Come on!
-It's just Yu-jin.

1389
00:52:52,435 --> 00:52:54,938
-She hates that!
-You can't do that!

1390
00:52:55,005 --> 00:52:56,606
-She had made it clear.
-She hates it!

1391
00:52:56,673 --> 00:52:58,808
It took half an hour
to make her feel better.

1392
00:52:58,875 --> 00:53:00,911
-She turned her face away.
-You're done for.

1393
00:53:00,977 --> 00:53:02,179
DISAPPOINTED

1394
00:53:03,079 --> 00:53:05,849
It was game over the moment
you called her with her surname.

1395
00:53:06,416 --> 00:53:07,717
You're done!

1396
00:53:07,784 --> 00:53:08,785
Don't even try.

1397
00:53:08,852 --> 00:53:09,853
I missed that.

1398
00:53:09,920 --> 00:53:11,821
-What is that?
-This.

1399
00:53:11,888 --> 00:53:13,190
-Did he make it?
-It's a new thing.

1400
00:53:13,256 --> 00:53:15,091
I've been promoting a new move.

1401
00:53:15,158 --> 00:53:17,594
-I missed that.
-"Missed"?

1402
00:53:17,661 --> 00:53:20,463
-My mistake. I missed that.
-Missed.

1403
00:53:20,530 --> 00:53:22,299
Don't play along.

1404
00:53:22,365 --> 00:53:24,034
It'll go viral.

1405
00:53:24,968 --> 00:53:26,903
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
BRAISED CHESTNUT, SWEET CHESTNUT, FIG JAM

1406
00:53:26,970 --> 00:53:29,039
INJEOLMI, APPLE, STRAWBERRY, LEMON JUICE,
HONEY, MILK, CREAM, INSTANT COFFEE

1407
00:53:29,105 --> 00:53:32,442
You're up against him, Chef Jong-won.
What dessert are you making?

1408
00:53:32,509 --> 00:53:36,580
I'm going to use many different types
of chestnuts that she has.

1409
00:53:36,646 --> 00:53:40,417
The beautiful Yu-jin
visited us here on the show,

1410
00:53:40,483 --> 00:53:44,955
so my dessert is called
It's a Beautiful Chest-Night.

1411
00:53:45,021 --> 00:53:46,856
IT'S A BEAUTIFUL CHEST-NIGHT

1412
00:53:46,923 --> 00:53:48,792
-We're done. The round is over!
-Game over.

1413
00:53:48,858 --> 00:53:50,627
-Come back.
-He does these unexpected cutesy things.

1414
00:53:50,694 --> 00:53:52,462
-That was cute.
-It was.

1415
00:53:52,529 --> 00:53:54,664
-It's over.
-It's a Beautiful Chest-Night.

1416
00:53:54,731 --> 00:53:56,933
I'll make something called <i>wonso-byeong</i>.

1417
00:53:57,000 --> 00:53:58,435
It's a traditional Korean dessert you eat

1418
00:53:58,501 --> 00:54:00,437
on the first full moon
of the lunar new year.

1419
00:54:00,503 --> 00:54:02,239
It's like Korean boba,

1420
00:54:02,305 --> 00:54:05,041
originally made
with rice balls and honey water.

1421
00:54:05,108 --> 00:54:08,578
But I'll be using chestnuts
and strawberries.

1422
00:54:08,645 --> 00:54:12,148
I'll also make <i>chalpyeon</i>
with the <i>injeolmi</i> she has,

1423
00:54:12,215 --> 00:54:15,352
-and <i>yul-ran</i> with chestnuts.
-<i>Yul-ran</i>, chestnut cookie.

1424
00:54:15,418 --> 00:54:18,455
Lastly, if I have enough time, I'll make
a beverage with braised chestnuts.

1425
00:54:18,521 --> 00:54:19,889
Four items?

1426
00:54:19,956 --> 00:54:23,059
There are many lesser-known
traditional Korean desserts,

1427
00:54:23,126 --> 00:54:26,930
so I thought many baby DIVEs
could watch this and become interested.

1428
00:54:26,997 --> 00:54:28,431
It'll be a great opportunity.

1429
00:54:28,498 --> 00:54:29,899
ARE YOU WATCHING, DIVE?

1430
00:54:29,966 --> 00:54:33,970
Let us begin the next round,
A Snack for Gen MZ.

1431
00:54:34,037 --> 00:54:37,507
The man who captured the hearts of Gen MZ,
and now even grade school children.

1432
00:54:37,574 --> 00:54:39,843
The president of kids, Chef Son Jong-won.

1433
00:54:39,909 --> 00:54:43,413
He had made chestnut tiramisu
before the Dubai chewy cookie craze!

1434
00:54:43,480 --> 00:54:46,983
The chestnut king, Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1435
00:54:47,050 --> 00:54:50,020
Which one of them will create a new fad?

1436
00:54:50,086 --> 00:54:53,290
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1437
00:54:54,090 --> 00:54:55,358
SWOOSH

1438
00:54:56,359 --> 00:54:58,595
1. MAKE SYRUP BY BOILING WATER,
SUGAR, LEMON JUICE, HONEY

1439
00:54:58,662 --> 00:55:01,064
It's a Beautiful Chest-Night
by the good vibes guy.

1440
00:55:01,131 --> 00:55:02,132
TUCKING

1441
00:55:02,198 --> 00:55:04,434
Desserts need a lot of work,
so he'll be busy.

1442
00:55:05,235 --> 00:55:06,803
I'm still worried,

1443
00:55:06,870 --> 00:55:09,673
wondering if Sung-jun can
successfully make kadayif.

1444
00:55:09,739 --> 00:55:12,876
Because the strands must
turn out very thin.

1445
00:55:12,942 --> 00:55:16,313
He has to create a very tiny outlet
for the batter,

1446
00:55:16,379 --> 00:55:18,982
and the batter must be consistent.

1447
00:55:19,049 --> 00:55:20,050
A-HA!

1448
00:55:20,116 --> 00:55:21,351
The flour must be mixed thoroughly.

1449
00:55:21,418 --> 00:55:22,719
It must be tough to do in 15 minutes.

1450
00:55:22,786 --> 00:55:24,187
I don't know when this began,

1451
00:55:24,254 --> 00:55:26,656
but Poong has been the only one
talking about the dishes.

1452
00:55:27,190 --> 00:55:29,359
Why aren't you doing it?

1453
00:55:29,426 --> 00:55:31,328
Poong has Jong-won on his back.

1454
00:55:31,394 --> 00:55:33,963
I was even tuned in.

1455
00:55:34,030 --> 00:55:35,699
We were all listening attentively.

1456
00:55:36,232 --> 00:55:37,233
COFFEE

1457
00:55:37,300 --> 00:55:40,804
They have to make a snack
that Gen MZ will love.

1458
00:55:40,870 --> 00:55:43,073
The GST is working hard on DCP.

1459
00:55:43,139 --> 00:55:44,708
1. MICROWAVE MILK AND BRAISED CHESTNUT

1460
00:55:46,343 --> 00:55:47,811
CHOP PUMPKIN INJEOLMI

1461
00:55:48,211 --> 00:55:50,914
Chef Jong-won puts <i>injeolmi</i> into a pot.

1462
00:55:50,980 --> 00:55:52,582
Are you going to steam those?

1463
00:55:52,649 --> 00:55:55,251
Yes, I want to make them softer.

1464
00:55:55,318 --> 00:55:59,689
Once it's steamed,
it'll stretch smoothly like mozzarella.

1465
00:56:00,156 --> 00:56:01,157
NEXT, FOR CHALPYEON

1466
00:56:01,224 --> 00:56:03,059
He's applying something on the rice cake.

1467
00:56:03,126 --> 00:56:05,628
-I put fig jam on it.
-Fig jam.

1468
00:56:05,695 --> 00:56:08,465
-Fig jam?
-She had fig jam?

1469
00:56:08,531 --> 00:56:10,066
He's making the batter.

1470
00:56:10,133 --> 00:56:11,501
-That's the kadayif batter.
-Kadayif.

1471
00:56:11,568 --> 00:56:12,569
Is that the batter?

1472
00:56:12,802 --> 00:56:13,870
WATER, OLIVE OIL

1473
00:56:14,237 --> 00:56:17,240
Kadayif batter is nothing special.
It's just a flour batter.

1474
00:56:17,307 --> 00:56:19,042
But he needs to make it consistently thin?

1475
00:56:19,109 --> 00:56:20,410
Yes, that's the problem.

1476
00:56:20,477 --> 00:56:23,913
If it gets severed or turns into drops,
then it's ruined.

1477
00:56:23,980 --> 00:56:25,715
2. MAKE BATTER FROM WATER,
OLIVE OIL, FLOUR, STARCH

1478
00:56:25,782 --> 00:56:27,851
-He needs to make it thin.
-Very thin.

1479
00:56:27,917 --> 00:56:28,918
Let's keep an eye on it.

1480
00:56:28,985 --> 00:56:32,021
-Yes.
-The viscosity looks fine.

1481
00:56:32,088 --> 00:56:33,990
-The viscosity seems okay.
-Does it?

1482
00:56:34,057 --> 00:56:35,425
He's using a water bottle.

1483
00:56:35,492 --> 00:56:37,560
How is he going to do it
with a water bottle?

1484
00:56:37,627 --> 00:56:38,962
Is he making holes?

1485
00:56:39,829 --> 00:56:40,830
PIERCED

1486
00:56:41,498 --> 00:56:43,099
-No way.
-The heat is important too.

1487
00:56:43,166 --> 00:56:44,567
He's about to begin.

1488
00:56:44,634 --> 00:56:46,803
-The kadayif show.
-Kadayif.

1489
00:56:46,870 --> 00:56:48,304
He'll begin the kadayif show.

1490
00:56:48,371 --> 00:56:51,107
-He'll begin the kadayif show.
-Kadayif.

1491
00:56:53,810 --> 00:56:55,712
WITNESSING HOMEMADE KADAYIF IN THE MAKING!

1492
00:56:55,779 --> 00:56:57,647
He's doing it.

1493
00:56:57,714 --> 00:57:00,417
-He's doing it.
-This is so cool.

1494
00:57:00,483 --> 00:57:01,484
Wow.

1495
00:57:01,551 --> 00:57:03,787
You took all
of Yu-jin's attention, Sung-jun.

1496
00:57:03,853 --> 00:57:05,054
She's only looking at you--

1497
00:57:05,121 --> 00:57:06,956
Hey, wow!

1498
00:57:07,891 --> 00:57:10,026
THERE IT IS!

1499
00:57:10,393 --> 00:57:11,461
WHOA!

1500
00:57:11,661 --> 00:57:12,896
WOW

1501
00:57:13,229 --> 00:57:14,931
SHOUT OUT TO SUNG-JUN

1502
00:57:15,365 --> 00:57:17,233
THE CROWD GOES WILD

1503
00:57:18,134 --> 00:57:19,369
HEY, YU-JIN

1504
00:57:19,436 --> 00:57:22,472
<i>Chefs should never say no</i>
<i>to a difficult challenge.</i>

1505
00:57:22,539 --> 00:57:23,506
YAY

1506
00:57:23,573 --> 00:57:24,774
-Sung-jun!
-He did it!

1507
00:57:25,041 --> 00:57:27,010
ONE MORE ROUND!

1508
00:57:27,677 --> 00:57:28,978
That's so fascinating.

1509
00:57:29,045 --> 00:57:30,513
It really is.

1510
00:57:30,580 --> 00:57:31,981
-He's doing it.
-It's working.

1511
00:57:32,048 --> 00:57:33,483
-He's making it with flour.
-No way.

1512
00:57:33,550 --> 00:57:36,186
He made the batter himself.
Let's take another look.

1513
00:57:36,252 --> 00:57:38,154
SECOND BATCH, SUCCESS

1514
00:57:38,354 --> 00:57:39,856
THAT'S SO COOL

1515
00:57:40,590 --> 00:57:42,225
TRYING NOT TO SMILE

1516
00:57:42,792 --> 00:57:43,626
A HUGE PILE

1517
00:57:43,827 --> 00:57:45,261
WOW

1518
00:57:45,728 --> 00:57:47,464
Yu-jin is clapping.

1519
00:57:47,697 --> 00:57:49,365
THIRD TIME'S THE CHARM

1520
00:57:49,432 --> 00:57:51,267
This is bad. He took everyone's attention.

1521
00:57:51,334 --> 00:57:52,335
GRIN

1522
00:57:52,869 --> 00:57:53,870
IT'S ALL RIGHT

1523
00:57:53,937 --> 00:57:55,104
You can stop, right? No?

1524
00:57:55,171 --> 00:57:56,473
-It's not a lot.
-It's not.

1525
00:57:56,539 --> 00:57:58,274
It's not a lot once you roll it up.

1526
00:57:58,341 --> 00:58:00,310
-It's the last batch.
-The last batch.

1527
00:58:01,311 --> 00:58:03,046
CLEAN

1528
00:58:04,347 --> 00:58:06,516
You can make a fortune
by selling that these days.

1529
00:58:07,150 --> 00:58:08,151
BUTTER

1530
00:58:08,218 --> 00:58:09,652
4. COOK KADAYIF IN BUTTER

1531
00:58:09,719 --> 00:58:11,254
He added butter.

1532
00:58:11,321 --> 00:58:12,489
He's trying to make it crispy.

1533
00:58:12,555 --> 00:58:14,057
He'll fry it now.

1534
00:58:14,123 --> 00:58:17,460
No one was watching
what Chef Jong-won was doing for a while.

1535
00:58:18,428 --> 00:58:19,762
He's peeling an apple.

1536
00:58:19,829 --> 00:58:23,266
-He was using lots of <i>injeolmi</i>.
-Yes, <i>injeolmi</i> and apple.

1537
00:58:23,333 --> 00:58:25,668
Look at how he's cutting the apple.

1538
00:58:25,735 --> 00:58:27,704
-Wow.
-He's different.

1539
00:58:27,770 --> 00:58:30,707
-It's as thin as a thread.
-It is.

1540
00:58:30,773 --> 00:58:31,774
ON TOP OF THE CHALPYEON

1541
00:58:33,510 --> 00:58:34,878
They're ready.

1542
00:58:34,944 --> 00:58:36,479
No, he's steaming it some more.

1543
00:58:36,546 --> 00:58:38,414
The <i>injeolmi</i> pieces have melted.

1544
00:58:38,481 --> 00:58:41,050
He must be doing that intentionally.

1545
00:58:41,551 --> 00:58:44,120
-That's what he wanted.
-It's completely melted.

1546
00:58:44,187 --> 00:58:48,258
He melted it to reshape it
in a way that he wants.

1547
00:58:48,825 --> 00:58:50,126
Hurry up.

1548
00:58:50,827 --> 00:58:52,929
What are you up to, Sung-jun?

1549
00:58:52,996 --> 00:58:54,364
I'm making braised chestnut cream.

1550
00:58:54,430 --> 00:58:57,000
The braised chestnut? Are you blending it?

1551
00:58:59,168 --> 00:59:00,403
It's looking smooth.

1552
00:59:00,470 --> 00:59:01,938
The cream is hot, but…

1553
00:59:02,005 --> 00:59:03,139
It's not blowing up.

1554
00:59:03,206 --> 00:59:04,207
TAP

1555
00:59:04,908 --> 00:59:06,776
SEPARATING EGG WHITES AND YOLKS

1556
00:59:08,545 --> 00:59:09,546
Meringue?

1557
00:59:09,612 --> 00:59:12,916
He's making meringue by hand.

1558
00:59:12,982 --> 00:59:14,517
He's taking a difficult path.

1559
00:59:14,584 --> 00:59:16,953
Sung-jun continues to
go down a difficult path.

1560
00:59:17,020 --> 00:59:18,721
You have 11 minutes left.

1561
00:59:18,788 --> 00:59:20,990
He only tries hard
whenever girl group members come.

1562
00:59:21,057 --> 00:59:22,692
GIVING HIS ALL

1563
00:59:22,759 --> 00:59:24,627
Because his limbs are shorter,

1564
00:59:24,694 --> 00:59:27,964
he can whisk the bowl much faster
than ordinary people. It's useful.

1565
00:59:28,031 --> 00:59:29,599
He definitely has an advantage.

1566
00:59:29,666 --> 00:59:31,701
People like me have to make big circles,

1567
00:59:31,768 --> 00:59:33,136
so I can't move as fast.

1568
00:59:33,202 --> 00:59:35,171
I'm getting a good workout today.

1569
00:59:35,238 --> 00:59:36,806
It's a good workout!

1570
00:59:37,206 --> 00:59:38,741
YOU CAN TAKE A BREAK, SUNG-JUN

1571
00:59:38,808 --> 00:59:39,809
BUT NO ONE'S RESTING

1572
00:59:39,876 --> 00:59:40,877
It's a good workout!

1573
00:59:40,944 --> 00:59:42,679
Sung-jun is doing his best.

1574
00:59:42,745 --> 00:59:43,746
SUCH A GOOD PARTNER

1575
00:59:44,380 --> 00:59:45,515
The kadayif.

1576
00:59:46,082 --> 00:59:47,917
DON'T FORGET ABOUT THE KADAYIF

1577
00:59:47,984 --> 00:59:51,387
-I'm going to be stressed out.
-Yes, you will be stressed out.

1578
00:59:51,454 --> 00:59:52,889
It's a good workout.

1579
00:59:52,956 --> 00:59:56,993
Unlike Sung-jun,
Chef Jong-won is moving about quietly.

1580
00:59:57,060 --> 00:59:59,429
COOLING LEMON SYRUP OVER ICE

1581
00:59:59,495 --> 01:00:03,600
-It's the syrup for <i>wonso-byeong</i>.
-It's the syrup,

1582
01:00:03,666 --> 01:00:05,702
but I'm making it with strawberries
instead of <i>omija</i>.

1583
01:00:05,768 --> 01:00:09,205
-Gosh.
-It'll give it a nice color.

1584
01:00:09,272 --> 01:00:10,607
7. BLEND LEMON SYRUP AND STRAWBERRY

1585
01:00:10,673 --> 01:00:12,909
Chef Jong-won loves strawberries.

1586
01:00:13,610 --> 01:00:15,144
WONSO-BYEONG SYRUP IS READY

1587
01:00:15,211 --> 01:00:17,547
-It looks so pretty.
-It's so pretty.

1588
01:00:17,780 --> 01:00:19,148
STILL NOISY ON THIS SIDE

1589
01:00:19,215 --> 01:00:20,316
I need to stop working out.

1590
01:00:21,651 --> 01:00:24,153
-Are you using a machine?
-An electric one.

1591
01:00:24,220 --> 01:00:26,623
-Ultimately using the machine.
-You're doing that after all that fuss?

1592
01:00:26,689 --> 01:00:28,157
That was just for show.

1593
01:00:28,224 --> 01:00:31,494
-The manual whisking.
-Yes, it was a performance.

1594
01:00:31,561 --> 01:00:33,396
This is quite a workout.

1595
01:00:33,663 --> 01:00:35,798
HE'S ALL TALK

1596
01:00:36,299 --> 01:00:37,934
EGG YOLK, MILK

1597
01:00:38,001 --> 01:00:40,603
What's that for, Sung-jun?

1598
01:00:41,304 --> 01:00:42,572
-He can't hear you.
-Answer him.

1599
01:00:42,639 --> 01:00:44,874
-What now? Me?
-Yes.

1600
01:00:44,941 --> 01:00:46,275
What's the thing with the egg yolk?

1601
01:00:46,342 --> 01:00:47,343
It's for the pancakes.

1602
01:00:47,410 --> 01:00:49,545
-Pancakes.
-That's pancake batter.

1603
01:00:49,612 --> 01:00:52,715
-He always does <i>mantecare</i> out of habit.
-Like this?

1604
01:00:52,782 --> 01:00:54,017
Pancake.

1605
01:00:54,083 --> 01:00:55,818
-He does this.
-<i>Mantecare</i>.

1606
01:00:55,885 --> 01:00:56,886
Come on out!

1607
01:00:59,389 --> 01:01:00,723
-It won't come out.
-It won't.

1608
01:01:00,790 --> 01:01:02,425
-It looks too thick.
-This is bad.

1609
01:01:02,492 --> 01:01:04,127
What will he use that for?

1610
01:01:04,193 --> 01:01:06,195
-Chestnut purée.
-Chestnut cream.

1611
01:01:06,262 --> 01:01:07,597
-Chestnut cream.
-Like purée.

1612
01:01:08,164 --> 01:01:09,632
He has the rice cake.

1613
01:01:09,699 --> 01:01:10,967
-Is that <i>injeolmi</i>?
-<i>Injeolmi</i>.

1614
01:01:11,034 --> 01:01:12,802
He puts lots of work into the <i>injeolmi</i>.

1615
01:01:12,869 --> 01:01:15,571
He's throwing it in cold water
to keep a circular shape.

1616
01:01:15,638 --> 01:01:18,107
-Did he reshape those?
-Into a ball.

1617
01:01:18,174 --> 01:01:19,809
-They'll be chewy.
-He detailed in his work.

1618
01:01:19,876 --> 01:01:20,877
NEXT, THE K-BOBA

1619
01:01:22,011 --> 01:01:23,112
Very delicate.

1620
01:01:23,179 --> 01:01:24,480
APPLE BOBA

1621
01:01:26,916 --> 01:01:28,551
He's balling strawberries too.

1622
01:01:31,921 --> 01:01:34,223
BRAISED CHESTNUT BOBA

1623
01:01:36,759 --> 01:01:38,594
He's making tiny balls.

1624
01:01:38,661 --> 01:01:41,698
-Yes.
-He steamed it to reshape it.

1625
01:01:41,764 --> 01:01:44,233
-He's making tiny ball shapes.
-Yes.

1626
01:01:44,300 --> 01:01:45,968
You have nine minutes and 30 seconds left.

1627
01:01:46,035 --> 01:01:48,604
Sung-jun is still working on the meringue.

1628
01:01:48,671 --> 01:01:51,741
-It takes a lot of work to make dessert.
-It does.

1629
01:01:51,808 --> 01:01:54,977
It takes a lot of work,
but you only get a tiny portion.

1630
01:01:55,044 --> 01:01:57,413
He mixed the meringue and egg yolks

1631
01:01:57,480 --> 01:02:00,883
to make the batter for soufflé pancake.

1632
01:02:01,150 --> 01:02:02,151
SIGH

1633
01:02:02,218 --> 01:02:04,020
Sung-jun is overwhelmingly seizing

1634
01:02:04,087 --> 01:02:07,056
everyone's attention during the process.

1635
01:02:07,123 --> 01:02:08,124
What's that?

1636
01:02:08,858 --> 01:02:10,393
He's mashing the chestnut.

1637
01:02:10,460 --> 01:02:11,894
It's like making Mont Blanc cake.

1638
01:02:11,961 --> 01:02:13,196
-It's for the <i>yul-ran</i>.
-<i>Yul-ran</i>.

1639
01:02:13,262 --> 01:02:15,364
-What's Jong-won doing?
-The chestnuts.

1640
01:02:15,431 --> 01:02:19,168
I'll mix this with honey
and reshape them into chestnuts.

1641
01:02:19,235 --> 01:02:22,805
He'll dip it in cinnamon
to make it look like chestnuts.

1642
01:02:23,072 --> 01:02:24,240
YUL-RAN!

1643
01:02:24,907 --> 01:02:26,776
-That came out nice.
-Wow.

1644
01:02:26,843 --> 01:02:28,878
That isn't an easy process.

1645
01:02:28,945 --> 01:02:31,114
He said it'd be soufflé pancakes,
but it looks ordinary.

1646
01:02:31,180 --> 01:02:32,949
No, I'll do more to it.

1647
01:02:33,282 --> 01:02:35,017
HE MUST HAVE A PLAN

1648
01:02:35,084 --> 01:02:38,087
You need to add more meringue.

1649
01:02:38,154 --> 01:02:40,056
-It has to rise.
-Yes.

1650
01:02:40,123 --> 01:02:42,425
Soufflé pancakes are very thick,

1651
01:02:42,492 --> 01:02:45,194
almost five to six centimeters thick.

1652
01:02:45,261 --> 01:02:48,264
But those look like <i>dorayaki</i> pancakes.

1653
01:02:49,398 --> 01:02:51,267
-It needs to jiggle.
-Yes.

1654
01:02:51,334 --> 01:02:54,737
Goodness.
Are you trying to deceive Yu-jin?

1655
01:02:54,804 --> 01:02:55,805
He's in a rush.

1656
01:02:55,872 --> 01:02:57,540
Trying to deceive the non-professional?

1657
01:02:57,607 --> 01:02:59,842
He'll use moisture to let it rise.

1658
01:02:59,909 --> 01:03:02,712
You have to do it properly.
Many people are watching you.

1659
01:03:04,113 --> 01:03:05,381
-Crispy.
-It looks crispy.

1660
01:03:05,448 --> 01:03:07,750
-It looks like stir-fried anchovies.
-Isn't it?

1661
01:03:07,817 --> 01:03:08,818
